Quoted By: >>26555466
>>26552869
It's a question without a purely objective solution; as such, I'll have you know I like your response very much, it just answers a different question. One of the fun things about character-writing's those little affects we weave into the fabric of a character, the affects (insecurities, attitudes, beliefs) that rule a character's behavior, factoring into his/her every interaction until he/she changes in some way. That step in planning can come before or after we decide where he/she's from, the culture of origin, backstory, etc. To your point, characters insecure about their backgrounds or just their manner of speech might attempt to conceal them, with little twangs or flourishes periodically slipping, and the circumstances under which that happens also compliments a character's development.

My question has more to do with the presentation of dialogue in a story; it assumes a character, say,
>>26553808
already speaks comfortably in her accent. If Comfy were to present her dialogue as phoneticized, he might have
>”Oy eckshully need t'pick ep a geeft for a behthday et wehk,” she said, “Noy oydea what to geet em’ thoy'h.”
Which would be heeeavily accented, or bogan in this case:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5j0UZEnaEH4

Now, the conventional way to present dialogue from characters with heavy accents entails describing it in the dialogue's tagging:
>”I actually need to pick up a gift for a birthday at work,” she said, her accent , “No idea what to get em’ though.”
and his/her use of slang, or, if English isn't his/her first language, through occasional flashes of non-English dialogue, or conversational dubiety ("Non, pas bon. Er, ehm, how do you say it... No, just no."):
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iwto58Wc2bg

So in summary, I'm concerned purely with how authors might go about presenting dialogue for their audiences rather than how characters concern themselves with the issues of being bilingual.
